 \mathopen {}\left \lparen a_0,b_0\right \rparen \mathclose {}
. The necessary identifications are obtained from the contractibility of A and Ba_0 by the characterisation of identifications in dependent sums (Definition , Example ).

Let \epsilon  \colon  f\circ  f^{-1} = 1_{B} be the counit of the inverse to f\colon  A\to  B. Given b:B, we must show that the fiber of f over b is contractible; the centre of contraction is given by the pair 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen f^{-1} x, \epsilon  x\right \rparen \mathclose {}
, and the required paths can be constructed via the univalence principle for fibers using the unit \eta \colon  f^{-1}\circ  f = 1_{A}, the coherence \chi \colon  \mathsf {act}_{f}\circ \eta \sim \epsilon \circ  f, and the naturality of homotopies.

For any type A we have a proposition \mathsf {toProp}\,{A} equipped with a unit map \eta _{\mathsf {prop}}\colon  A \to \mathsf {toProp}\,{A}; moreover, we have the following induction principle: for any family of propositions B\colon  \mathsf {toProp}\,A \to  \mathsf {Prop}, any function b\colon  \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{
